# Network Topologies

## Definition

Network topology describes the physical or logical arrangement of devices and connections in a network.

It defines how computers, switches, routers, and other devices are connected and how data flows between them.

A topology can be:

- Physical topology: How devices are physically connected
- Logical topology: How data moves through the network

---

# Bus Topology

## Overview

In a bus topology, all devices share a single central communication line called a backbone.

Every device is connected to the same cable.

## Characteristics

- Simple design
- Low cost
- Easy to implement in small networks

## Advantages

- Requires less cable
- Easy to set up

## Disadvantages

- If the main cable fails, the entire network goes down
- Performance decreases with more devices
- Difficult to troubleshoot

## Example

Older Ethernet networks.

---

# Star Topology

## Overview

In a star topology, all devices connect to a central device, usually a switch.

The switch manages communication between devices.

## Characteristics

- Most common modern topology
- Uses switches or access points

## Advantages

- Easy to manage
- Easy to add new devices
- Failure of one device does not affect others

## Disadvantages

- If the central switch fails, the network stops
- Requires more cable

## Example

Most home and office networks.

---

# Ring Topology

## Overview

In a ring topology, devices are connected in a circular structure.

Data travels from one device to another until it reaches the destination.

## Characteristics

- Each device has two connections
- Data usually moves in one direction

## Advantages

- Predictable data flow
- Can handle traffic efficiently

## Disadvantages

- Failure of one connection can affect the entire network
- Harder to maintain

---

# Mesh Topology

## Overview

In a mesh topology, devices have multiple connections between them.

Each device can communicate through different paths.

## Types

### Full Mesh

Every device connects directly to every other device.

### Partial Mesh

Only important devices have multiple connections.

## Advantages

- High reliability
- Redundant paths
- If one connection fails, another path can be used

## Disadvantages

- Expensive
- Complex installation

## Example

Internet backbone networks.

---

# Tree Topology

## Overview

A tree topology combines characteristics of star and bus topologies.

Devices are organized in a hierarchical structure.

## Characteristics

- Uses multiple levels
- Common in large organizations

## Advantages

- Easy to expand
- Supports large networks

## Disadvantages

- Failure in a higher-level device can affect many devices
- More complex management

---

# Hybrid Topology

## Overview

A hybrid topology combines two or more different topologies.

Examples:

- Star + Mesh
- Star + Ring

## Advantages

- Flexible
- Can be customized for different needs

## Disadvantages

- More complex
- Higher cost

---

# Topology Comparison

| Topology | Main Idea | Reliability |
|---|---|---|
| Bus | Single backbone cable | Low |
| Star | Central switch | Medium/High |
| Ring | Circular connection | Medium |
| Mesh | Multiple paths | High |
| Tree | Hierarchical structure | Medium |
| Hybrid | Combination | Depends on design |

---

# Cybersecurity Importance

Understanding network topologies helps security professionals:

- Identify critical devices
- Understand traffic flow
- Find possible points of failure
- Design better security controls
- Analyze attack paths

Network structure affects how attacks spread and how defenses should be implemented.
